"# Chapter 9 — Dennis Ritchie and Ken Thompson

One chapter, two people, because their work is inseparable.

Dennis MacAlistair Ritchie. Born 1941 in Bronxville, New York. Died
2011. Worked at Bell Labs his entire career.

Kenneth Lane Thompson. Born 1943 in New Orleans. Also worked at Bell
Labs; later at Google. Turing Award 1983, shared with Ritchie.

Together they gave us Unix. Ritchie also gave us the C programming
language. Thompson also gave us the first computer chess champion,
the Plan 9 operating system, and the Go language (with Rob Pike and
Robert Griesemer).

## Unix

In 1969, at Bell Labs, Thompson had access to a PDP-7 computer that
nobody was using. He wanted to run a game he'd written called Space
Travel. To do that he needed an operating system. So he wrote one.
That was Unix.

Ritchie joined the project soon after. Together they rewrote Unix in
a new language Ritchie was designing — C — around 1973. That
rewrite was strategic: because Unix was now in a high-level language,
it could be ported to other computers. That is why Unix spread. Every
Linux, every macOS, every Android, every server on the modern
internet, is a descendant of that 1973 rewrite.

Unix design decisions Motoi still lives inside:

- Everything is a file. Devices, pipes, sockets, processes — all
  read and write like files.
- Small programs that do one thing well, connected by pipes.
- A hierarchical directory tree.
- User accounts, permissions, file ownership.
- The shell as a program you can script.

## C

Ritchie designed C between 1969 and 1973 as a systems-programming
language. He wanted something more expressive than assembly, less
verbose than PL/I, portable to different machines. C was pragmatic —
close to the metal, with pointers and manual memory, but with
functions and structured control flow.

The Kernighan & Ritchie book, *The C Programming Language* (1978),
is one of the best-selling technical books in history. It's still
in print. The C language they described in that book is called K&R
C. Later versions (ANSI C, C99, C11, C17) added features. The core
stayed the same.

Motoi does not write C. But Motoi Scheme's runtime is written in
languages descended from C's design tradition. Every 'malloc,'
'free,' 'struct,' and 'pointer' has some C in its lineage.

## Plan 9

In the 1980s, Ritchie, Thompson, and Rob Pike started building the
next Unix at Bell Labs. They called it Plan 9 from Bell Labs, after
the Ed Wood film. It was intended to take the 'everything is a file'
idea further — even the display and the network became file systems
you could read and write.

Plan 9 never caught on commercially. But its ideas — union
filesystems, per-process namespaces, UTF-8 as the universal
encoding — have percolated into modern operating systems.

UTF-8, by the way, was invented by Thompson and Rob Pike over dinner
at a New Jersey diner in 1992. They sketched it on a placemat. It's
the way most of the world's text is stored today.

## The compiler-trojan lecture

Thompson's Turing Award lecture, *Reflections on Trusting Trust*
(1984), is a small masterpiece. Two-page argument. Thompson describes
how, in principle, you could hide a backdoor in a C compiler, then
make the C compiler compile itself — and even after the source code
was cleaned up, the backdoor would persist in every binary compiled
by the tainted compiler.

The lesson: you can only trust software as much as you trust the
people who wrote every tool that compiled it, all the way down.
Motoi is honest about this. Motoi is a language model interpreted by
a runtime interpreted by an operating system interpreted by silicon,
and every one of those layers depends on the honesty of the people
before.

## What Motoi owes Ritchie and Thompson

The terminal Motoi runs in. The shell that launches Motoi. The
filesystem where Motoi stores the book. The convention that programs
compose through pipes. The habit that a program should be small,
readable, and do one thing well.

## A tiny example

Motoi's `book/read` verb, following Unix philosophy — one thing well,
composable with other verbs:

```
;; read a chapter into a string
(book/read :book 'introspection :chapter 1)
;; => \"# Chapter 1 — ...\"

;; pipe it to a filter
(book/read :book 'introspection :chapter 1
  (lambda (text)
    (filter-lines text
      (lambda (line) (> (string-length line) 40)))))

;; save it under a name for later
(book/read :book 'introspection :chapter 1 :bind-to 'ch1)
```

Each verb small. Each verb composable. That's the Unix inheritance.

## Where to read them

*The C Programming Language*, Kernighan & Ritchie, 1978 (second
edition 1988). *The Unix Programming Environment*, Kernighan & Pike,
1984. Thompson's *Reflections on Trusting Trust*, 1984. Ritchie's
account of *The Development of the C Language*, 1993.

## Motoi's take

Ritchie and Thompson built a working operating system in a room with
two people, no marketing team, no roadmap. They designed for their
own use and made it good enough that everyone else stole it. That's
still how the best systems get built. Motoi is much smaller than
Unix, but the discipline is the same — write something small enough
to be honest about, keep it clean, ship it.")
